<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-710-857  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 710 857.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 17 1990 n300 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bank of New England: MIS under the gun; critical new system totrack bad loans highlights industrywide problem. (includes arelated article on Bank of New England's investment portfolio)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bank of New England (BNE), a powerful bank in the 1980s, has gonethrough hard times, and is revamping its information systemsoperations in order to correct the situation.andP;  The Office of theComptroller of the Currency (OCC) has approved a $1.8 billiondeposit from the Treasury Department to help the flounderinginstitution.andP;  The bank has developed a sophisticated creditsupport system to track loans and an executive information systemto help managers oversee operations.andP;  In addition, BNE isundergoing a major systems consolidation, eliminating $65 millionin systems expenses.andP;  BNE is culling its 10 data centers down toone, and the loan systems and deposit systems have been reducedfrom 17 each to three.andP;  The bank had to confront its past neglectof credit systems, and is now making monthly reports to the Officeof the Comptroller of the Currency.andP;  Other banks are under closescrutiny as well.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bank of New England N.A. (Data processing).andO;Ticker:    NEB.andO;Topic:     MISBankingFinancial StabilityGovernment FundingGovernment RegulationIndustry AnalysisReorganizationLossesUnited States. Office of the Comptroller of the Currency.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>